TY  - JOUR
T1  - More Women in Tech? Evidence from a Field Experiment Addressing Social Identity
AU  - Del Carpio, Lucía
AU  - Guadalupe, Maria
Y1  - 2021/08/18
PY  - 2021
DA  - 2022/05/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.2021.4035
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.2021.4035
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - 3196
EP  - 3218
VL  - 68
IS  - 5
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - We study the impact of using informational messaging aimed at encouraging women to seek a career in technology and the resulting trade-offs for organizations pursuing recruitment strategies of this kind. Our treatment, implemented through two field experiments among potential applicants to a five-month software-coding program targeted at low-income women in Peru and Mexico, counterbalances the strong male stereotype associated with a career in tech. Although our informational messages substantially increase application rates, including candidates at the top of the cognitive skill distribution, they introduce negative selection on cognitive skills, implying a higher cost of screening. Moreover, we observe selection on the noncognitive dimensions addressed with the treatment (e.g., stronger gender stereotypes and traditional norms). This points to the barriers that preclude more women from applying to tech positions, as well as the trade-offs for organizations of adopting such a strategy.This paper was accepted by Alfonso Gambardella, business strategy.
AB  - We study the impact of using informational messaging aimed at encouraging women to seek a career in technology and the resulting trade-offs for organizations pursuing recruitment strategies of this kind. Our treatment, implemented through two field experiments among potential applicants to a five-month software-coding program targeted at low-income women in Peru and Mexico, counterbalances the strong male stereotype associated with a career in tech. Although our informational messages substantially increase application rates, including candidates at the top of the cognitive skill distribution, they introduce negative selection on cognitive skills, implying a higher cost of screening. Moreover, we observe selection on the noncognitive dimensions addressed with the treatment (e.g., stronger gender stereotypes and traditional norms). This points to the barriers that preclude more women from applying to tech positions, as well as the trade-offs for organizations of adopting such a strategy.This paper was accepted by Alfonso Gambardella, business strategy.
