TY  - JOUR
T1  - Funding Liquidity and Market Liquidity: The Broker-Dealer Perspective
AU  - Macchiavelli, Marco
AU  - Zhou, Xing (Alex)
Y1  - 2021/06/15
PY  - 2021
DA  - 2022/05/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.2021.4053
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.2021.4053
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - 3379
EP  - 3398
VL  - 68
IS  - 5
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - We provide direct evidence of how dealers? funding liquidity affects their liquidity provision in securities markets. Worse funding liquidity (higher repo haircuts and rates) leads to larger bid-ask spreads and transaction costs in corporate bonds. We also find that dealers? relationships with money funds are important determinants of their repo haircuts and rates. Using dealers? exposure to the 2016 Securities and Exchange Commission (SEC) money fund reform as an instrument, we show that funding liquidity indeed has a causal effect on market liquidity. Finally, dealers with lower funding liquidity tend to have smaller market shares and execute more trades on an agency basis.This paper was accepted by Haoxiang Zhu, finance.
AB  - We provide direct evidence of how dealers? funding liquidity affects their liquidity provision in securities markets. Worse funding liquidity (higher repo haircuts and rates) leads to larger bid-ask spreads and transaction costs in corporate bonds. We also find that dealers? relationships with money funds are important determinants of their repo haircuts and rates. Using dealers? exposure to the 2016 Securities and Exchange Commission (SEC) money fund reform as an instrument, we show that funding liquidity indeed has a causal effect on market liquidity. Finally, dealers with lower funding liquidity tend to have smaller market shares and execute more trades on an agency basis.This paper was accepted by Haoxiang Zhu, finance.
