JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - 3625
EP  - 3634
VL  - 68
IS  - 5
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - We organize and extend findings on the comparative static effects of risk changes on optimal behavior in a unifying expected utility model. We determine restrictions on preferences for clear-cut results. Risk increases of a benefit are compensated by lowering exposure to risk. For risk increases of a cost, the response depends on the order of the risk change. This discrepancy arises because even-order risk increases of a cost raise the riskiness of the payoff distribution, whereas odd-order risk increases of a cost reduce it. We identify the stochastic dominance orders to resolve this discrepancy and discuss specific decision problems as applications.This paper was accepted by Manel Baucells, behavioral economics and decision analysis.
